# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: funds-for-endangered-parrots
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The **Americas**, sometimes collectively called **America**, are a landmass comprising the totality of North America and South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] When viewed as a single continent, the Americas are the second largest continent by area after Asia and the third largest continent by population.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere and constitute the "New World", in contrast to the "Old World" of Afro-Eurasia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Along with their associated islands, the Americas cover 8% of Earth's total surface area and 28.4% of its land area.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The topography is dominated by the American Cordillera, a long chain of mountains that runs the length of the west coast.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The flatter eastern side of the Americas is dominated by large river basins, such as the Amazon, St.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Lawrence River–Great Lakes, Mississippi, and La Plata basins.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Since the Americas extend 14,000 km (8,700 mi) from north to south, the climate and ecology vary widely, from the arctic tundra of Northern Canada, Greenland, and Alaska, to the tropical rainforests in Central America and South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Humans first settled the Americas from Asia between 20,000 and 16,000 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] A second migration of Na-Dene speakers followed later from Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The subsequent migration of the Inuit into the neoarctic c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] 3500 BCE completed what is generally regarded as the settlement by the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Norse colonization of North America saw several settlements established in Greenland, and perhaps on the mainland, however, these were later abandoned.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Spanish presence involved the enslavement of large numbers of the indigenous population of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Diseases introduced from Europe and West Africa devastated the indigenous peoples, and the European powers colonized the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Mass emigration from Europe, including large numbers of indentured servants, and importation of African slaves largely replaced the indigenous peoples in much of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution in the 1770s and largely ended with the Spanish–American War in the late 1890s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Americas are home to more than a billion inhabitants, two-thirds of whom reside in the United States, Brazil, and Mexico.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The name "America" was first recorded in 1507.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] A world map created by Martin Waldseemüller was the earliest recorded use of the term.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The name was also used (together with the related term *Amerigen*) in the *Cosmographiae Introductio*, apparently written by Matthias Ringmann, in reference to South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] It was applied to both North and South America by Gerardus Mercator in 1538.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] "America" derives from *Americus*, the Latin version of the Italian explorer Amerigo Vespucci's first name.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The feminine form *America* was originally used to refer to the newly discovered continent, which is why it was accorded with the feminine names of the other continents: Asia, Africa, and Europa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Since the 1950s, however, North America and South America have generally been considered by English speakers as separate continents, and taken together are called *the Americas*, or more rarely *America*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] When conceived as a unitary continent, the form is generally *the continent of America* in the singular.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] However, without a clarifying context, singular *America* in English commonly refers to the United States of America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The region was initially termed America or New India on the Mercator maps.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Speakers of English generally refer to the landmasses of North America and South America as *the Americas*, the *Western Hemisphere*, or the *New World*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The adjective *American* may be used to indicate something pertaining to the Americas, but this term is primarily used in English to indicate something pertaining to the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Some non-ambiguous alternatives exist, such as the adjective *Pan-American*, or *New Worlder* as a demonym for a resident of the closely related New World.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Use of *America* in the hemispherical sense is sometimes retained, or can occur when translated from other languages.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] For example, the Association of National Olympic Committees (ANOC) in Paris maintains a single continental association for "America", represented by one of the five Olympic rings.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Mencken said, "The Latin-Americans use Norteamericano in formal writing, but, save in Panama, prefer nicknames in colloquial speech." To avoid "American" one can use constructed terms in their languages derived from "United States" or even "North America".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In Canada, its southern neighbor is often referred to as "the United States", "the U.S.A.", or (informally) "the States", while U.S. citizens are generally referred to as "Americans".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Most Canadians resent being referred to as "Americans".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In Spanish, *América* is a single continent composed of the subcontinents of *América del Sur* and *América del Norte*, the land bridge of *América Central*, and the islands of the *Antillas*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] *Americano* or *americana* in Spanish refers to a person from *América* in a similar way that in which *europeo* or *europea* refers to a person from *Europa*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The terms *sudamericano/a*, *centroamericano/a*, *antillano/a* and *norteamericano/a* can be used to more specifically refer to the location where a person may live.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Also, the term *norteamericano* (North American) may refer to a citizen of the United States, though in formal writing it is less common since it is used for the inhabitants of North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In Portuguese, *América* is a single continent composed of *América do Sul* (South America), *América Central* (Central America) and *América do Norte* (North America).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] It can be ambiguous, as *América* can be used to refer to the United States of America, but is avoided in print and formal environments.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The demonym 'American' (americano) is commonly used in Portuguese to refer to people from the United States, although the terms 'norte-americano', 'estadounidense' or 'estadunidense' also formally exist and are preferred by those who wish to distinguish it from the continental demonym.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In French, the word *américain* may be used for things relating to the Americas; however, similar to English, it is most often used for things relating to the United States, with the term *états-unien* sometimes used for clarity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] *Panaméricain* may be used as an adjective to refer to the Americas without ambiguity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] French speakers may use the noun *Amérique* to refer to the whole landmass as one continent, or two continents, *Amérique du Nord* and *Amérique du Sud*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In French, *Amérique* is seldom used to refer to the United States, leading to some ambiguity when it is.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Similar to English usage, *les Amériques* or *des Amériques* is used to refer unambiguously to the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In Dutch, the word *Amerika* mostly refers to the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Although the United States is equally often referred to as *de Verenigde Staten* ("the United States") or *de VS* ("the US"), *Amerika* relatively rarely refers to the Americas, but it is the only commonly used Dutch word for the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] This often leads to ambiguity; and to stress that something concerns the Americas as a whole, Dutch uses a combination, namely *Noord- en Zuid-Amerika* (North and South America).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Latin America and Central America are generally referred to as *Latijns Amerika* and *Midden-Amerika* respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The adjective *Amerikaans* is most often used for things or people relating to the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] There are no alternative words to distinguish between things relating to the United States or to the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Dutch uses the local alternative for things relating to elsewhere in the Americas, such as *Argentijns* for Argentine, etc.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The term *Pre-Columbian* is used especially often in the context of the great indigenous civilizations of the Americas, such as those of Mesoamerica (Olmec, Toltec, Teotihuacano, Zapotec, Mixtec, Aztec, Maya) and the Andean civilizations (Inca, Moche, Chavín, Muisca, Cañari).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Many pre-Columbian civilizations established characteristics and hallmarks which included permanent or urban settlements, agriculture, civic and monumental architecture, and complex societal hierarchies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Some of these civilizations had long faded by the time of the first permanent European arrivals (c. late 15th–early 16th centuries), and are known only through archeological investigations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Others were contemporary with this period, and are also known from historical accounts of the time.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] A few, such as the Maya, had their own written records.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] However, most Europeans of the time viewed such texts as pagan, and much was destroyed in Christian pyres.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Only a few hidden documents remain today, leaving modern historians with glimpses of ancient culture and knowledge.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The first inhabitants migrated into the Americas from Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Habitation sites are known in Alaska and Yukon from at least 20,000 years ago, with suggested ages of up to 40,000 years.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Beyond that, the specifics of the Paleo-Indian migration to and throughout the Americas, including the dates and routes traveled, are subject to ongoing research and discussion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Widespread habitation of the Americas occurred after the Late Glacial Maximum, from 16,000 to 13,000 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The traditional theory has been that these early migrants moved into the Beringia land bridge between eastern Siberia and present-day Alaska about 40,000–17,000 years ago, when sea levels were significantly lowered during the Quaternary glaciation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] These people are believed to have followed herds of now-extinct pleistocene megafauna along *ice-free corridors* that stretched between the Laurentide and Cordilleran ice sheets.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Another route proposed is that, either on foot or using primitive boats, they migrated down the Pacific coast to South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Evidence of the latter would since have been covered by a sea level rise of hundreds of meters following the last ice age.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Both routes may have been taken, although the genetic evidences suggests a single founding population.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The micro-satellite diversity and distributions specific to South American Indigenous peoples indicates that certain populations have been isolated since the initial colonization of the region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] A second migration occurred after the initial peopling of the Americas; Na Dene speakers, found predominantly in North American groups at varying genetic rates, with the highest frequency found among the Athabaskans at 42%, derive from this second wave.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Linguists and biologists have reached a similar conclusion based on analysis of Amerindian language groups and ABO blood group system distributions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Then the people of the Arctic small tool tradition, a broad cultural entity that developed along the Alaska Peninsula, around Bristol Bay, and on the eastern shores of the Bering Strait c.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Arctic small tool tradition, a Paleo-Eskimo culture, branched off into two cultural variants, including the Pre-Dorset and the Independence traditions of Greenland.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The descendants of the Pre-Dorset cultural group, the Dorset culture, were displaced by the final migrants from the Bering sea coast line, the Thule people (the ancestors of modern Inuit), by 1000 CE.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Around the same time as the Inuit migrated into Greenland, Viking settlers began arriving in Greenland in 982 and Vinland shortly thereafter, establishing a settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows, near the northernmost tip of Newfoundland.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Although there had been previous trans-oceanic contact, large-scale European colonization of the Americas began with the first voyage of Christopher Columbus in 1492.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The first Spanish settlement in the Americas was La Isabela in northern Hispaniola.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] This town was abandoned shortly after in favor of Santo Domingo de Guzmán, founded in 1496, the oldest American city of European foundation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] This was the base from which the Spanish monarchy administered its new colonies and their expansion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Santo Domingo was subject to frequent raids by English and French pirates.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] On the continent, Panama City on the Pacific coast of Central America, founded on August 15, 1519, played an important role, being the base for the Spanish conquest of South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Conquistador Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón established San Miguel de Guadalupe, the first European settlement in what is now the United States, on the Pee Dee River in South Carolina.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] During the first half of the 16th century, Spanish colonists conducted raids throughout the Caribbean Basin, bringing captives from Central America, northern South America, and Florida back to Hispaniola and other Spanish settlements.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] France, led by Jacques Cartier and Giovanni da Verrazzano, focused primarily on North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] English explorations of the Americas were led by Giovanni Caboto and Sir Walter Raleigh.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Dutch in New Netherland confined their operations to Manhattan Island, Long Island, the Hudson River Valley, and what later became New Jersey.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The spread of new diseases brought by Europeans and African slaves killed many of the inhabitants of North America and South America, with a general population crash of Native Americans occurring in the mid-16th century, often well ahead of European contact.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] One of the most devastating diseases was smallpox.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] European immigrants were often part of state-sponsored attempts to found colonies in the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Migration continued as people moved to the Americas fleeing religious persecution or seeking economic opportunities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Millions of individuals were forcibly transported to the Americas as slaves, prisoners or indentured servants.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution and the Haitian Revolution in the late 1700s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] This was followed by numerous Latin American wars of independence in the early 1800s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Between 1811 and 1825, Paraguay, Argentina, Chile, Gran Colombia, the United Provinces of Central America, Mexico, Brazil, Peru, and Bolivia gained independence from Spain and Portugal in armed revolutions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] After the Dominican Republic won independence from Haiti, it was re-annexed by Spain in 1861, but reclaimed its independence in 1865 at the conclusion of the Dominican Restoration War.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The last violent episode of decolonization was the Cuban War of Independence which became the Spanish–American War, which resulted in the independence of Cuba in 1898, and the transfer of sovereignty over Puerto Rico from Spain to the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Peaceful decolonization began with the United States's purchase of Louisiana from France in 1803, Florida from Spain in 1819, Alaska from Russia in 1867, and the Danish West Indies from Denmark in 1916.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Canada became independent of the United Kingdom, starting with the Balfour Declaration of 1926 and the Statute of Westminster 1931 and ending with the patriation of the Canadian Constitution in 1982.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Dominion of Newfoundland similarly achieved independence under the Balfour Declaration and Statute of Westminster, but relinquished self-rule in 1934.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] It was subsequently confederated with Canada in 1949.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The remaining European colonies in the Caribbean began to achieve peaceful independence well after World War II.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago became independent in 1962, and Guyana and Barbados both achieved independence in 1966.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the 1970s, the Bahamas, Grenada, Dominica, St.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Vincent and the Grenadines all became independent of the United Kingdom, and Suriname became independent of the Netherlands.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Belize, Antigua and Barbuda, and Saint Kitts and Nevis achieved independence from the United Kingdom in the 1980s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The northernmost point of the Americas is Kaffeklubben Island, which is the most northerly point of land on Earth.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The southernmost undisputed point is Águila Islet, although the Antarctic islands of Southern Thule are sometimes taken into account.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The mainland of the Americas is the world's longest north-to-south landmass.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The distance between its two polar extremities, Murchison Promontory on the Boothia Peninsula in northern Canada and Cape Froward in Chilean Patagonia, is roughly 14,000 km (8,700 mi).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The mainland's most westerly point is the end of the Seward Peninsula in Alaska; Attu Island, further off the Alaskan coast to the west, is considered the westernmost point of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Ponta do Seixas in northeastern Brazil forms the easternmost extremity of the mainland, while Nordostrundingen, in Greenland, is the most easterly point of the continental shelf.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] South America broke off from the west of the supercontinent Gondwana about 135 million years ago, forming its own continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] About 15 million years ago, the collision of the Caribbean Plate and the Pacific Plate resulted in the emergence of a series of volcanoes along the border that created a number of islands.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The gaps in the archipelago of Central America filled in with material eroded off North America and South America, plus new land created by continued volcanism.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] By three million years ago, the continents of North America and South America were linked by the Isthmus of Panama, thereby forming the single landmass of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Great American Interchange resulted in many species being spread across the Americas, such as the cougar, procyonids, porcupines, opossums, armadillos, and hummingbirds.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The geography of the western Americas is dominated by the American Cordillera, with the Andes running along the west coast of South America and the Rocky Mountains and other North American Cordillera ranges running along the western side of North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The 2,300-kilometer-long (1,400 mi) Appalachian Mountains run along the east coast of North America from Alabama to Newfoundland.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] North of the Appalachians, the Arctic Cordillera runs along the eastern coast of Canada.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The largest mountain ranges are the Andes and Rocky Mountains.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Sierra Nevada and the Cascade Range reach similar altitudes as the Rocky Mountains, but are significantly smaller.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In North America, the greatest number of fourteeners are in the United States, and more specifically in the US state of Colorado.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The highest peaks of the Americas are located in the Andes, with Aconcagua of Argentina being the highest; in North America Denali (Mount McKinley) in the US state of Alaska is the tallest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Between its coastal mountain ranges, North America has vast flat areas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Interior Plains spread over much of the continent, with low relief.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Canadian Shield covers almost 5 million km2 of North America and is generally quite flat.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Similarly, the north-east of South America is covered by the flat Amazon basin.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Brazilian Highlands on the east coast are fairly smooth but show some variations in landform, while farther south the Gran Chaco and Pampas are broad lowlands.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The climate of the Americas varies significantly from region to region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Tropical rainforest climate occurs in the latitudes of the Amazon, American cloud forests, southeastern Florida and Darién Gap.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the Rocky Mountains and Andes, dry and continental climates are observed.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Often the higher altitudes of these mountains are snow-capped.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Southeastern North America is well known for its occurrence of tornadoes and hurricanes, of which the vast majority of tornadoes occur in the United States' Tornado Alley, as well as in the southerly Dixie Alley in the North American late-winter and early spring seasons.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Often parts of the Caribbean are exposed to the violent effects of hurricanes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] These weather systems are formed by the collision of dry, cool air from Canada and wet, warm air from the Atlantic.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] With coastal mountains and interior plains, the Americas have several large river basins that drain the continents.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The largest river basin in North America is that of the Mississippi, covering the second-largest watershed on the planet.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Mississippi–Missouri river system drains most of 31 states of the United States, most of the Great Plains, and large areas between the Rocky and Appalachian mountains.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Mississippi–Missouri is the fourth-longest river system and has the tenth-greatest discharge in the world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In North America, to the east of the Appalachian Mountains, there are no major rivers but rather a series of rivers and streams that flow east with their terminus in the Atlantic Ocean, such as the Hudson, Saint John, and Savannah rivers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] A similar instance arises with central Canadian rivers that drain into Hudson Bay; the largest being the Churchill River.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] On the west coast of North America, the main rivers are the Colorado, Columbia, Yukon, Fraser, and Sacramento rivers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Colorado River drains much of the Southern Rockies and parts of the Basin and Range Province.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The river flows approximately 1,450 miles (2,330 km) into the Gulf of California, during which over time it has carved out natural phenomena such as the Grand Canyon and created phenomena such as the Salton Sea.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Columbia is a large river, 1,243 miles (2,000 km) long, in central western North America and is the most powerful river on the West Coast of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the far northwest of North America, the Yukon drains much of the Alaskan peninsula and flows 1,980 miles (3,190 km) from parts of Yukon and the Northwest Territory to the Pacific.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Draining to the Arctic Ocean of Canada, the Mackenzie River drains waters from the Arctic Great Lakes of Arctic Canada, as opposed to the St Lawrence River that drains the Great Lakes of southern Canada into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The Mackenzie River is the largest in Canada and drains 1,805,200 km2 (697,000 mi2).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The largest river basin in South America is that of the Amazon, which has the highest volume flow of any river on Earth.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The second largest watershed of South America is that of the Paraná River, which covers about 2,582,074 km2 (996,944 mi2).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] North America and South America began to develop a shared population of flora and fauna about 2.5 million years ago, when continental drift brought the two continents into contact via the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Initially, the exchange of biota was roughly equal, with North American genera migrating into South America in about the same proportions as South American genera migrated into North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] This exchange is known as the Great American Interchange.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The exchange became lopsided after roughly a million years, with the total spread of South American genera into North America far more limited in scope than the spread of North American genera into South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In exports and imports, in 2020, the United States was the world's second largest exporter (US$1.64 trillion) and the largest importer (US$2.56 trillion).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Mexico was the tenth largest exporter and importer.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Canada was the twelfth largest exporter and importer.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Brazil was the 24th largest exporter and the 28th largest importer.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Chile was the 45th largest exporter and the 47th largest importer.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Argentina was the 46th largest exporter and the 52nd largest importer.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Colombia was the 54th largest exporter and the 51st largest importer; among others.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] The agriculture of the continent is very strong and varied.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Countries such as United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, and Argentina are among the largest agricultural producers on the planet.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In livestock, the Americas are major producers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In industrial terms, the World Bank lists the top producing countries each year, based on the total value of production.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the production of oil, the continent had 8 of the 30 largest world producers in 2020: United States (1st), Canada (4th), Brazil (8th), Mexico (14th), Colombia (20th), Venezuela (26th), Ecuador (27th), and Argentina (28th).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the production of natural gas, the continent had 8 of the 32 largest world producers in 2015: United States (1st), Canada (5th), Argentina (18th), Trinidad and Tobago (20th), Mexico (21st), Venezuela (28th), Bolivia (31st), and Brazil (32nd).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the production of coal, the continent had 5 of the 30 largest world producers in 2018: United States (3rd), Colombia (12th), Canada (13th), Mexico (24th), and Brazil (27th).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the production of vehicles, the continent had 5 of the 30 largest world producers in 2019: United States (2nd), Mexico (7th), Brazil (9th), Canada (12th), and Argentina (28th).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] In the production of steel, the continent had 5 of the 31 largest world producers in 2019: United States (4th), Brazil (9th), Mexico (15th), Canada (18th), and Argentina (31st).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p01] Haiti has the lowest GDP per capita in the Americas, although its economy was growing slightly as of 2016.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] A city proper is the locality with legally fixed boundaries and an administratively recognized urban status that is usually characterized by some form of local government.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] An urban area is characterized by higher population density and vast human features in comparison to areas surrounding it.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Urban areas may be cities, towns or conurbations, but the term is not commonly extended to rural settlements such as villages and hamlets.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Urban areas are created and further developed by the process of urbanization and do not include large swaths of rural land, as do metropolitan areas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] that is socio-economically connected to the urban core city, typically by employment ties through commuting, with the urban core city being the primary labor market.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] In accordance with these definitions, the three largest population centers in the Americas are: Mexico City, anchor to the largest metropolitan area in the Americas; New York City, anchor to the largest urban area in the Americas; and São Paulo, the largest city proper in the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] All three cities maintain Alpha classification and large scale influence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The population of the Americas is made up of the descendants of four large ethnic groups and their combinations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Latin America is typically contrasted with Anglo-America, where English, a Germanic language, is prevalent, and which comprises Canada (with the exception of Francophone Canada rooted in Latin Europe [France]—see Quebec and Acadia) and the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Both countries are located in North America, with cultures deriving predominantly from British and other Germanic roots.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The transatlantic slave trade brought millions of Africans to the territories of the Americas under the colonial rule of European powers, especially South America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] In South America, Portugal played a significant role in the trafficking of enslaved Africans, with estimates suggesting that about 40% of all Africans forcibly brought to the Americas were taken to Brazil alone, to work primarily in sugar cane plantations, mining, and agricultural endeavors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] In North America, the British Empire was heavily involved in the transatlantic slave trade, with the establishment of colonies such as Virginia, where enslaved Africans were primarily used as labor in tobacco plantations and later in other agricultural and domestic sectors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] This system perpetuated for centuries, shaping the socio-economic landscape of all nations of the hemisphere.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] After the Haitian Revolution led by Jean-Jacques Dessalines, which started in 1791 and was the only successful slave revolt in history, the world's first black republic was established.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] It started with the massacre of the white population, between 3,000 and 5,000 white men and women of all ages were killed.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Oui, nous avons rendu à ces vrais cannibales guerre pour guerre, crimes pour crimes, outrages pour outrages.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Oui, j’ai sauvé mon pays, j’ai vengé l’Amérique.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Yes, I have saved my country – I have avenged America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Other faiths include Buddhism; Hinduism; Sikhism; Baháʼí Faith; a wide variety of indigenous religions, many of which can be categorized as animistic; new age religions and many African and African-derived religions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Syncretic faiths can also be found throughout the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Various languages are spoken in the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Some are of European origin, others are spoken by indigenous peoples or are the mixture of various languages like the different creoles.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The most widely spoken first language in the Americas is Spanish, followed by English and Portuguese.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The dominant language of Latin America is Spanish, though the most populous nation in Latin America, Brazil, speaks Portuguese.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Small enclaves of French-, Dutch- and English-speaking regions also exist in Latin America, notably in French Guiana, Suriname, and Belize and Guyana respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Haitian Creole is dominant in the nation of Haiti, where French is also spoken.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Native languages are more prominent in Latin America than in Anglo-America, with Nahuatl, Quechua, Aymara, and Guaraní as the most common.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Various other native languages are spoken with less frequency across both Anglo-America and Latin America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Creole languages other than Haitian Creole are also spoken in parts of Latin America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The dominant language of Anglo-America is English.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] French is also official in Canada, where it is the predominant language in Quebec and an official language in New Brunswick along with English.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] It is also an important language in Louisiana, and in parts of New Hampshire, Maine, and Vermont.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Spanish has kept an ongoing presence in the Southwestern United States, which formed part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain, especially in California and New Mexico, where a distinct variety of Spanish spoken since the 17th century has survived.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] It has more recently become widely spoken in other parts of the United States because of heavy immigration from Latin America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] High levels of immigration in general have brought great linguistic diversity to Anglo-America, with over 300 languages known to be spoken in the United States alone, but most languages are spoken only in small enclaves and by relatively small immigrant groups.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Most of the non-native languages have, to different degrees, evolved differently from the mother country, but are usually still mutually intelligible.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Some have combined, however, which has even resulted in completely new languages, such as Papiamento, which is a combination of Portuguese, Spanish, Dutch (representing the respective colonizers), native Arawak, various African languages, and, more recently English.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The lingua franca Portuñol, a mixture of Portuguese and Spanish, is spoken in the border regions of Brazil and neighboring Spanish-speaking countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] More specifically, Riverense Portuñol is spoken by about 100,000 people in the border regions of Brazil and Uruguay.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Because of immigration, there are many communities where other languages are spoken from all parts of the world, especially in the United States, Brazil, Argentina, Canada, Chile, Costa Rica, and Uruguay—very important destinations for immigrants.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in the Americas, having spread through the hemisphere after the growth of US influence in the late 19th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] It overtook cricket, a fellow bat-and-ball sport spread by earlier British influence, in most places outside of the Commonwealth Caribbean.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Other American sports, such as basketball, have grown throughout the region over time.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] Football is perhaps the most popular and followed sport in the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The North American region which also includes the Central and Caribbean national associations is overseen by the CONCACAF, while the South American region and its national teams are represented by the CONMEBOL.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/americas-p02] The following is a list of multinational organizations in the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia shares the landmass of Eurasia with Europe, and of Afro-Eurasia with both Europe and Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In general terms, it is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean, and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The border of Asia with Europe is a historical and cultural construct, as there is no clear physical and geographical separation between them.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] A commonly accepted division places Asia to the east of the Suez Canal separating it from Africa; and to the east of the Turkish straits, the Ural Mountains and Ural River, and to the south of the Caucasus Mountains and the Caspian and Black seas, separating it from Europe.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Since the concept of Asia derives from the term for the eastern region from a European perspective, Asia is the remaining vast area of Eurasia minus Europe.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Therefore, Asia is a region where various independent cultures coexist rather than sharing a single culture, and its boundary with Europe is somewhat arbitrary and has moved since its first conception in classical antiquity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The division of Eurasia into two continents reflects East–West cultural differences, some of which vary on a spectrum.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] China and India traded places as the largest economies in the world from 1 to 1800 CE.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] China was a major economic power for much of recorded history, with the highest GDP per capita until 1500.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Silk Road became the main east–west trading route in the Asian hinterlands while the Straits of Malacca stood as a major sea route.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia has exhibited economic dynamism as well as robust population growth during the 20th century, but overall population growth has since fallen.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia was the birthplace of most of the world's mainstream religions including Islam, Judaism, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism, and many other religions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia varies greatly across and within its regions with regard to ethnic groups, cultures, environments, economics, historical ties, and government systems.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The term "Asia" is believed to originate in the Bronze Age toponym *Assuwa* (Hittite: 𒀸𒋗𒉿, romanized: *aš-šu-wa*) which originally referred only to a portion of northwestern Anatolia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The term appears in Hittite records recounting how a confederation of Assuwan states including Troy unsuccessfully rebelled against the Hittite king Tudhaliya I around 1400 BCE.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Roughly contemporary Linear B documents contain the term *aswia* (Mycenaean Greek: 𐀀𐀯𐀹𐀊, romanized: *a-si-wi-ja*), seemingly in reference to captives from the same area.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Herodotus used the term in reference to Anatolia and the territory of the Achaemenid Empire, in contrast to Greece and Egypt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] He reports that Greeks assumed that Asia was named after the wife of Prometheus, but that Lydians say it was named after *Asies*, son of Cotys, who passed the name on to a tribe at Sardis.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In Greek mythology, "Asia" (Ἀσία or Ἀσίη) was the name of a "Nymph or Titan goddess of Lydia".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Iliad (attributed by the ancient Greeks to Homer) mentions two Phrygians in the Trojan War named Asios (literally 'Asian'); and also a marsh or lowland containing a marsh in Lydia as ασιος.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The term was later adopted by the Romans, who used it in reference to the province of Asia, located in western Anatolia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] One of the first writers to use Asia as a name of the whole continent was Pliny.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The threefold division of the Old World into Africa, Asia, and Europe has been in use since the 6th century BCE, due to Greek geographers such as Anaximander and Hecataeus.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Anaximander placed the boundary between Asia and Europe along the Phasis River (now the Rioni) in Georgia of Caucasus (from its mouth by Poti on the Black Sea coast, through the Surami Pass and along the Kura River to the Caspian Sea), a convention still followed by Herodotus in the 5th century BCE.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] During the Hellenistic period, this convention was revised, and the boundary between Europe and Asia was now considered to be the Tanais (the modern Don River).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This is the convention used by Roman era authors such as Posidonius, Strabo and Ptolemy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Europe was later redefined by European academics.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In 1730, five years after the death of Peter the Great, Philip Johan von Strahlenberg published in Sweden a new atlas proposing the Ural Mountains as the border of Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Vasily Tatishchev announced that he had proposed the idea to von Strahlenberg.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The latter had suggested the Emba River as the southern part of this boundary.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Over the next century various proposals were made until the Ural River prevailed in the mid-19th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The border had been moved perforce from the Black Sea (the Romans' definition) to the Caspian Sea into which the Emba and Ural rivers project.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Between the Black Sea and the Caspian, the border is often placed along the crest of the Caucasus Mountains, although it is sometimes placed further north, on the Kuma–Manych Depression.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The boundary between Asia and Africa is the Suez Canal, the Gulf of Suez, the Red Sea, and the Bab-el-Mandeb.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This makes Egypt a transcontinental country, with the Sinai Peninsula in Asia and the remainder of the country in Africa.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Oceania is usually placed somewhere in the Indonesian Archipelago, specifically in Eastern Indonesia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Wallace Line separates the Asian and Wallacea biogeographical realms, a transition zone of deep water straits between the Asian and Australian continental shelves.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Weber's Line split the region in two with regard to the balance of fauna between Asian origin or Australo-Papuan origin.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Wallacea's eastern boundary with Sahul is represented by the Lydekker's Line.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Maluku Islands (except the Aru Islands) are often considered to lie on the border of southeast Asia, with the Aru Islands and Western New Guinea, to the east of the Lydekker's Line, being wholly part of Oceania, as both lie on the Australian continental plate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Culturally, the Wallacea region denoted the transition between Austronesian and Melanesian people, with varying degrees of intermixing between the two.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In general, the further west and coastal a region is, the stronger the Austronesian influences, and the further east and inland a region is, the stronger the Melanesian influences.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The terms Southeast Asia and Oceania, devised in the 19th century, have had several vastly different geographic meanings since their inception.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The chief factor in determining which islands of the Indonesian Archipelago are Asian has been the location of the colonial possessions of the various empires there (not all European).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Bering Strait and Bering Sea separate the landmasses of Asia and North America, as well as forming the international boundary between Russia and the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This national and continental boundary separates the Diomede Islands in the Bering Strait, with Big Diomede in Russia and Little Diomede in the United States.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are an island chain extending westward from the Alaskan Peninsula toward Russia's Komandorski Islands and Kamchatka Peninsula.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are sometimes associated with Oceania, owing to their status as remote Pacific islands, and their proximity to the Pacific Plate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This is extremely rare however, due to their non-tropical biogeography, as well as their inhabitants, who have historically been related to the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Lawrence Island in the northern Bering Sea belongs to the US state of Alaska and may be associated with either continent but is almost always considered part of North America, as with the Rat Islands in the Aleutian chain.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] At their nearest points, Alaska and Russia are separated by only 4 kilometres (2.5 miles).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Geographical Asia is a cultural artifact of European conceptions of the world, beginning with the Ancient Greeks, being imposed onto other cultures, an imprecise concept causing endemic contention about what it means.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia does not exactly correspond to the cultural borders of its various types of constituents.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] From the time of Herodotus, a minority of geographers have rejected the three-continent system (Europe, Africa, Asia) on the grounds that there is no substantial physical separation between them.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] For example, Sir Barry Cunliffe, the emeritus professor of European archeology at Oxford, argues that Europe has been geographically and culturally merely "the western excrescence of the continent of Asia".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Geographically, Asia is the major eastern constituent of the continent of Eurasia with Europe being a northwestern peninsula of the landmass.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia, Europe and Africa make up a single continuous landmass—Afro-Eurasia—and share a common continental shelf.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Almost all of Europe and a major part of Asia sit atop the Eurasian Plate, adjoined on the south by the Arabian and Indian Plate and with the easternmost part of Siberia (east of the Chersky Range) on the North American Plate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] About 1.8 million years ago, *Homo erectus* left the African continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This species is believed to have lived in East and Southeast Asia from 1.8 million to 110,000 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Researchers believe that the modern human, or *Homo sapiens*, migrated about 60,000 years ago to South Asia along the Indian Ocean.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Modern humans interbred with an archaic human species called Denisovans in Southeast Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Before the arrival of modern humans, Flores was occupied by *Homo floresiensis*, a small archaic human.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Ancestors of East Eurasians split from Ancient West Eurasians about 46,000 years ago, migrating out of the hub in the Iranian Plateau.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The history of Asia can be seen as the distinct histories of several peripheral coastal regions: East Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, Central Asia, and West Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The coastal periphery was home to some of the world's earliest known civilisations, each of them developing around fertile river valleys.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The civilisations in Mesopotamia, the Indus Valley and the Yellow River shared many similarities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] These civilisations may well have exchanged technologies and ideas such as mathematics and the wheel.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Other innovations, such as writing, seem to have been developed individually in each area.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Cities, states and empires developed in these lowlands.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The central steppe region had long been inhabited by horse-mounted nomads who could reach all areas of Asia from the steppes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The earliest postulated expansion out of the steppe is that of the Indo-Europeans, who spread their languages into West Asia, South Asia, and the borders of China, where the Tocharians resided.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The northernmost part of Asia, including much of Siberia, was largely inaccessible to the steppe nomads, owing to the dense forests, climate and tundra.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] These areas remained very sparsely populated.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The center and the peripheries were mostly kept separated by mountains and deserts.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Caucasus and Himalaya mountains and the Karakum and Gobi deserts formed barriers that the steppe horsemen could cross only with difficulty.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] While the urban city dwellers were more advanced technologically and socially, in many cases they could do little in a military aspect to defend against the mounted hordes of the steppe.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] However, the lowlands did not have enough open grasslands to support a large equestrian force; for this and other reasons, the nomads who conquered states in China, India, and the Middle East often found themselves adapting to the local, more affluent societies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Mongol Empire conquered a large part of Asia in the 13th century, an area extending from China to Europe.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Before the Mongol invasion, Song dynasty reportedly had approximately 120 million citizens; the 1300 census which followed the invasion reported roughly 60 million people.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Black Death, one of the most devastating pandemics in human history, is thought to have originated in the arid plains of central Asia, where it then travelled along the Silk Road.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] European involvement in Asia became more significant from the Age of Discovery onward, with Iberian-sponsored sailors such as Christopher Columbus and Vasco da Gama paving the way for new routes from Atlantic Europe to Pacific Asia and the Indian Ocean respectively in the late 15th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Russian Empire also began to expand into northwestern Asia from the 17th century, and would eventually take control of all of Siberia and most of Central Asia by the end of the 19th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Among non-European empires, the Ottoman Empire controlled Anatolia, most of the Middle East, North Africa and the Balkans from the mid 16th century onward, while in the 17th century, the Manchu conquered China and established the Qing dynasty.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Islamic Mughal Empire (preceded by the Delhi Sultanate of the 13th to early 16th century) and the Hindu Maratha Empire controlled much of India in the 16th and 18th centuries respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Western imperialism in Asia from the 18th to 20th centuries coincided with the Industrial Revolution in the West and the dethroning of India and China as the world's foremost economies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Around this time, Western powers started to dominate China in what later became known as the century of humiliation, with the British-supported opium trade and later Opium Wars resulting in China being forced into an unprecedented situation of importing more than it exported.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] One significant influence on Japan had been the United States, which had begun projecting influence across the Pacific after its early-to-mid-19th century westward expansion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The breakup of the Ottoman Empire in the early 20th century led to the Middle East also being contested and partitioned by the British and French.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] With the end of World War II in 1945 and the wartime ruination of Europe and imperial Japan, many countries in Asia were able to rapidly free themselves of colonial rule.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The independence of India came along with the carving out of a separate nation for the majority of South Asian Muslims, which in 1971 further split into Pakistan and Bangladesh; The Cold War in Asia strained relations between India and Pakistan and affected Asia more generally.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The end of the Cold War and the Soviet Union by 1991 saw the independence of the five modern Central Asian countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Some Arab countries took economic advantage of massive oil deposits that were discovered in their territory, becoming globally influential, though stability in the Middle East has been affected since 1948 by the Arab–Israeli conflict and American-led interventions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] East Asian nations (along with Singapore in Southeast Asia) became economically prosperous with high-growth "tiger economies"; China, having undergone the reform and opening up under Deng Xiaoping, regained its place among the top two economies of the world by the 21st century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] It covers 9% of the Earth's total surface area (or 30% of its land area), and has the longest coastline, at 62,800 kilometres (39,022 mi).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia is generally defined as comprising the eastern four-fifths of Eurasia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] It is located to the east of the Suez Canal and the Ural Mountains, and south of the Caucasus Mountains (or the Kuma–Manych Depression) and the Caspian and Black Seas.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] It is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia is subdivided into 49 countries, five of them (Georgia, Azerbaijan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Turkey) are transcontinental countries lying partly in Europe.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Geographically, Russia is partly and mostly in Asia, but is considered a European nation, both culturally and politically.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Gobi Desert is in Mongolia and the Arabian Desert stretches across much of the Middle East.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Yangtze in China is the longest river in the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The Himalayas between Nepal and China is the tallest mountain range in the world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Tropical rainforests stretch across much of southern Asia and coniferous and deciduous forests lie farther north.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Between 1990 and 2000 the area of primary forest in Asia decreased by 1.06 million hectares per year, between 2000 and 2015 it decreased by 280 000 ha per year.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] There are various approaches to the regional division of Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The following subdivision into regions is used, among others, by the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This division of Asia into regions by the United Nations is done solely for statistical reasons and does not imply any assumption about political or other affiliations of countries and territories.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia has extremely diverse climate features.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Climates range from Arctic and subarctic in Siberia to tropical in southern India and Southeast Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] It is moist across southeast sections, and dry across much of the interior.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Some of the largest daily temperature ranges on Earth occur in western sections of Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The monsoon circulation dominates across southern and eastern sections, due to the presence of the Himalayas forcing the formation of a thermal low which draws in moisture during the summer.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Southwestern sections of the continent are hot.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Siberia is one of the coldest places in the Northern Hemisphere, and can act as a source of arctic air masses for North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The most active place on Earth for tropical cyclone activity lies northeast of the Philippines and south of Japan.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Climate change is particularly important in Asia, as the continent accounts for the majority of the human population.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Warming since the 20th century is increasing the threat of heatwaves across the entire continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Heatwaves lead to increased mortality, and the demand for air conditioning is rapidly accelerating as the result.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] By 2080, around 1 billion people in the cities of South and Southeast Asia are expected to experience around a month of extreme heat every year.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The impacts on water cycle are more complicated: already arid regions, primarily located in West Asia and Central Asia, will see more droughts, while areas of East, Southeast and South Asia which are already wet due to the monsoons will experience more flooding.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The waters around Asia are subjected to the same impacts as elsewhere, such as the increased warming and ocean acidification.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] There are many coral reefs in the region, and they are highly vulnerable to climate change, to the point practically all of them will be lost if the warming exceeds 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia's distinctive mangrove ecosystems are also highly vulnerable to sea level rise.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia also has more countries with large coastal populations than any other continent, which would cause large economic impacts from sea level rise.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Water supplies in the Hindu Kush region will become more unstable as its enormous glaciers, known as the "Asian water towers", gradually melt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] These changes to water cycle also affect vector-borne disease distribution, with malaria and dengue fever expected to become more prominent in the tropical and subtropical regions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Food security will become more uneven, and South Asian countries could experience significant impacts from global food price volatility.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Historical emissions from Asia are lower than those from Europe and North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] However, China has been the single largest emitter of greenhouse gases in the 21st century, while India is the third-largest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] As a whole, Asia currently accounts for 36% of world's primary energy consumption, which is expected to increase to 48% by 2050.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] By 2040, it is also expected to account for 80% of the world's coal and 26% of the world's natural gas consumption.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] While the United States remains the world's largest oil consumer, by 2050 it is projected to move to third place, behind China and India.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] While nearly half of the world's new renewable energy capacity is built in Asia, this is not yet sufficient in order to meet the goals of the Paris Agreement.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] They imply that the renewables would account for 35% of total energy consumption in Asia by 2030.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Climate change adaptation is already a reality for many Asian countries, with a wide range of strategies attempted across the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Important examples include the growing implementation of climate-smart agriculture in certain countries or the "sponge city" planning principles in China.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] While some countries have drawn up extensive frameworks such as the Bangladesh Delta Plan or Japan's Climate Adaptation Act, others still rely on localized actions that are not effectively scaled up.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The most democratic countries in Asia are Japan, Taiwan and South Korea according to the V-Dem Democracy indices.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Within the states mentioned above are several partially recognized countries with limited to no international recognition.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia is both the largest continental economy in the world by both GDP nominal and PPP values and the world's fastest growing economic region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] As of 2026, China is by far the largest economy on the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] It is followed by India, Japan, South Korea, Turkey, Indonesia, Saudi Arabia, and Taiwan, which are all ranked among the top 20 largest economies by both nominal GDP and PPP values.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Based on Global Office Locations 2011, Asia dominated global office locations with 4 of the top 5 being in Asia: Hong Kong, Singapore, Tokyo and Seoul.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Around 68% of international firms have an office in Hong Kong.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the economy of China had an average annual growth rate of more than 8%.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] According to economic historian Angus Maddison, India had the world's largest economy for much of the past three millennia prior to the 19th century, accounting for 25% of the world's industrial output.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] China was the largest and most advanced economy on Earth for much of recorded history and shared the mantle with India.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] For several decades in the late twentieth century, Japan was the largest economy in Asia and second-largest in the world, after surpassing the Soviet Union (measured in net material product) in 1990 and Germany in 1968.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This ended in 2010, when China overtook Japan to become the world's second largest economy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In 2025, India overtook Japan in terms of nominal GDP to become the world's 4th largest and Asia's 2nd largest economy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Japan's GDP by currency exchange rates was almost as large as that of the rest of Asia combined.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In 1995, Japan's economy nearly equaled that of the US as the largest economy in the world for a day, after the Japanese currency reached a record high of 79 yen/US$.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Economic growth in Asia since World War II to the 1990s had been concentrated in Japan as well as South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Singapore, known as the Four Asian Tigers, which are now all considered developed economies, having among the highest GDP per capita in Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia is the largest continent in the world by a considerable margin, and it is rich in natural resources, such as petroleum, forests, fish, water, rice, copper and silver.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Manufacturing in Asia has traditionally been strongest in East and Southeast Asia, particularly in China, Taiwan, South Korea, Japan, India, the Philippines, and Singapore.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Japan and South Korea continue to dominate in the area of multinational corporations, though increasingly China and India are making significant inroads.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Many companies from Europe, North America, South Korea, and Japan have operations in Asia's developing countries to take advantage of its abundant supply of cheap labour and relatively developed infrastructure.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] According to Citigroup in 2011, 9 of 11 Global Growth Generator countries came from Asia driven by population and income growth.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] They are Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Iraq, Mongolia, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, and Vietnam.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia has three main financial centers: Hong Kong, Tokyo, and Singapore.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Call centers and business process outsourcing firms (BPOs) are becoming major employers in India and the Philippines due to the availability of a large pool of highly skilled, English-speaking workers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The increased use of outsourcing has assisted the rise of India and the China as financial centers.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Due to its large and extremely competitive information technology industry, India has become a major hub for outsourcing.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Trade between Asian countries and countries on other continents is largely carried out via sea routes.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] A far smaller part of the goods traffic runs via South Africa to Europe.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] A particularly significant part of Asian goods traffic is carried out on the Pacific Rim, toward Los Angeles and Long Beach.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The melting of the Arctic is also paving the way for new shipping routes from Northeast Asia to Europe and North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The land route to Europe is also the subject of construction projects, comparatively smaller in scope.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Intra-Asian trade, including sea trade, is growing rapidly.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In 2010, Asia had 3.3 million millionaires (people with net worth over US$1 million excluding their homes), slightly below North America's 3.4 million.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In 2011, Asia topped Europe in the number of millionaires.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Citigroup in The Wealth Report 2012 stated that the total wealth of people in Asia with over $100 million in assets exceeded that of their North American counterparts for the first time, as the world's "economic center of gravity" continued moving east.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] At the end of 2011, there were 18,000 people in Asia, mainly in Southeast Asia, China, and Japan, with at least $100 million in disposable assets, compared to North America with 17,000 and Western Europe with 14,000.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Asia's electricity demand has quadrupled since 2000 (rising from 4,199 TWh to over 16,000 TWh in 2024).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This growth, driven largely by China and increasingly by India, Indonesia, and Viet Nam, makes Asia the fastest-growing region for electricity demand globally, at about 5% per year.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] The region now accounts for about 36% of global primary energy consumption, a share projected to approach 50% by 2050.: 1468 Fossil fuels remain central in Asia: 66% of its energy is generated from fossil fuels, and Asia makes up 83% of the world's coal generation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] However, coal is slowly being phased out and natural gas is displacing oil and oil products in various sectors, supported by policies and regulations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] Natural gas demand in emerging market and developing economies in Asia expanded by around 6% in 2024, accounting for nearly 40% of incremental global gas demand.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] At the same time, Asia is the global leader in renewable energy expansion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] It is currently the only region on track to meet the goal of tripling renewable capacity by 2030, largely due to China, the leading nation in renewable energy generation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] China's wind and solar capacity has surged in recent years, together overtaking that of coal, while in 2024 India become the world's third largest generator of electricity from wind and solar.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] In 2013, with regional tourism growing and dominated by Chinese visitors, MasterCard released the Global Destination Cities Index report, in which 10 of 20 cities are Asian and Pacific cities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p01] This was also the first time an Asian city (Bangkok) was in the number one spot, with 15.98 million international visitors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] East Asia had by far the strongest overall Human Development Index (HDI) improvement of any region in the world, nearly doubling average HDI attainment over the past 40 years, according to the report's analysis of health, education and income data.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] China, the second highest achiever in the world in terms of HDI improvement since 1970, is the only country on the "Top 10 Movers" list due to income rather than health or education achievements.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Its per capita income increased a stunning 21-fold over the last four decades, also lifting hundreds of millions out of income poverty.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Yet it was not among the region's top performers in improving school enrollment and life expectancy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Nepal, a South Asian country, emerges as one of the world's fastest movers since 1970 mainly due to health and education achievements.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Its present life expectancy is 25 years longer than in the 1970s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] More than four of every five children of school age in Nepal now attend primary school, compared to just one in five 40 years ago.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Hong Kong ranked highest among the countries grouped on the HDI (number 7 in the world, which is in the "very high human development" category), followed by Singapore (9), Japan (19) and South Korea (22).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Afghanistan (155) ranked lowest amongst Asian countries out of the 169 countries assessed.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Asia is home to several language families and many language isolates.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Most Asian countries have more than one language that is natively spoken.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] For instance, according to Ethnologue, more than 700 languages are spoken in Indonesia, more than 400 languages spoken in India, and more than 100 are spoken in the Philippines.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] China has many languages and dialects in different provinces.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Many of the world's major religions have their origins in Asia, including the five most practiced in the world (excluding irreligion), which are Christianity, Islam, Hinduism, Chinese folk religion (classified as Confucianism and Taoism), and Buddhism.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The story of the Great Flood for example, as presented to Jews in the Hebrew Bible in the narrative of Noah—and later to Christians in the Old Testament, and to Muslims in the Quran—is earliest found in Mesopotamian mythology, in the Enûma Eliš and *Epic of Gilgamesh*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Hindu mythology similarly tells about an avatar of Vishnu in the form of a fish who warned Manu of a terrible flood.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Ancient Chinese mythology also tells of a Great Flood spanning generations, one that required the combined efforts of emperors and divinities to control.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The Abrahamic religions including Judaism, Christianity, Islam, Druze faith, and Baháʼí Faith originated in West Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Jews are the predominant ethnic group in Israel (75.6%) numbering at about 6.1 million, although the levels of adherence to Jewish religion vary.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Outside of Israel there are small ancient Jewish communities in Turkey (17,400), Azerbaijan (9,100), Iran (8,756), India (5,000) and Uzbekistan (4,000), among many other places.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] As of 2016, there are am estimated 14.4–17.5 million (2016, est.) Jews alive in the world today, making them one of the smallest Asian minorities, at roughly 0.3–0.4& of the total population of the continent.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Christianity is a widespread religion in Asia, with more than 286 million adherents in 2010 according to Pew Research Center, and nearly 364 million according to Britannica Book of the Year 2014.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Christians constitute around 12.6% of the total population of Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In the Philippines and Timor-Leste, Catholicism is the predominant religion; it was introduced by the Spaniards and the Portuguese, respectively.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In Armenia and Georgia, Eastern Orthodoxy is the predominant religion.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In the Middle East, such as in the Levant, Anatolia and Fars, Syriac Christianity (Church of the East) and Oriental Orthodoxy are prevalent minority denominations, which are both Eastern Christian sects mainly adhered to Assyrian people or Syriac Christians.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Vibrant indigenous minorities in West Asia are adhering to the Eastern Catholic Churches and Eastern Orthodoxy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Saint Thomas Christians in India trace their origins to the evangelistic activity of Thomas the Apostle in the 1st century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Significant Christian communities also found in Central Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia and East Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Islam, which originated in the Hejaz located in modern-day Saudi Arabia, is the second largest and most widely-spread religion in Asia with at least 1 billion Muslims constituting around 23.8% of the total population of Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] With 12.7% of the world Muslim population, the country currently with the largest Muslim population in the world is Indonesia, followed by Pakistan (11.5%), India (10%), Bangladesh, Iran and Turkey.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Mecca, Medina and Jerusalem are the three holiest cities for Islam in all the world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The Hajj and Umrah attract large numbers of Muslim devotees from all over the world to Mecca and Medina.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The Druze originated in West Asia, is a monotheistic religion based on the teachings of figures like Hamza ibn Ali and al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, and Greek philosophers such as Plato and Aristotle.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The number of Druze people worldwide is around one million.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Around 45–50% live in Syria, 35% to 40% live in Lebanon, and less than 10% live in Israel.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Recently there has been a growing Druze diaspora.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The Baháʼí Faith originated in Asia, in Iran (Persia), and spread from there to the Ottoman Empire, Central Asia, India, and Burma during the lifetime of Bahá'u'lláh.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Since the middle of the 20th century, growth has particularly occurred in other Asian countries, because Baháʼí activities in many Muslim countries has been severely suppressed by authorities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Lotus Temple is a big Baháʼí temple in India.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Almost all Asian religions have philosophical character and Asian philosophical traditions cover a large spectrum of philosophical thoughts and writings.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Indian philosophy includes Hindu philosophy and Buddhist philosophy.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] They include elements of nonmaterial pursuits, whereas another school of thought from India, Cārvāka, preached the enjoyment of the material world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism and Sikhism originated in India, South Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In East Asia, particularly in China and Japan, Confucianism, Taoism and Zen Buddhism took shape.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] As of 2012, Hinduism has around 1.1 billion adherents.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The faith represents around 25% of Asia's population and is the largest religion in Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] However, it is mostly concentrated in South Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Over 80% of the populations of both India and Nepal adhere to Hinduism, alongside significant communities in Bangladesh, Pakistan, Bhutan, Sri Lanka and Bali, Indonesia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Many overseas Indians in countries such as Burma, Singapore and Malaysia also adhere to Hinduism.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Buddhism has a great following in Mainland Southeast Asia and East Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The Communist-governed countries of China, Vietnam and North Korea are officially atheist, thus the number of Buddhists and other religious adherents may be under-reported.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Jainism is found mainly in India and in overseas Indian communities such as the United States and Malaysia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Sikhism is found in Northern India and amongst overseas Indian communities in other parts of Asia, especially Southeast Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Confucianism is found predominantly in mainland China, South Korea, Taiwan and in overseas Chinese populations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Taoism is found mainly in mainland China, Taiwan, Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In many Chinese communities, Taoism is easily syncretised with Mahayana Buddhism, thus exact religious statistics are difficult to obtain and may be understated or overstated.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The culture of Asia is a diverse blend of customs and traditions that have been practiced by the various ethnic groups of the continent for centuries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The continent is divided into six geographic sub-regions: Central Asia, East Asia, North Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and West Asia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] These regions are defined by their cultural similarities, including common religions, languages, and ethnicities.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] West Asia, also known as Southwest Asia or the Middle East, has cultural roots in the ancient civilisations of the Fertile Crescent and Mesopotamia, which gave rise to the Persian, Arab, Ottoman empires, as well as the Abrahamic religions of Judaism, Christianity and Islam.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] These civilisations, which are located in the Hilly flanks, are among the oldest in the world, with evidence of farming dating back to around 9000 BCE.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Despite the challenges posed by the vast size of the continent and the presence of natural barriers such as deserts and mountain ranges, trade and commerce have helped to create a Pan-Asian culture that is shared across the region.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Rabindranath Tagore, a Bengali dramatist and author from Santiniketan (now in West Bengal, India), won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1913, becoming the first Asian Nobel laureate.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The prize was awarded for Tagore's prose works and poetry, which had a significant additional impact on national literatures throughout the Western world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Tagore also authored both the Indian and Bangladeshi national anthems.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Other Asian writers who won Nobel Prize for literature include Yasunari Kawabata (Japan, 1968), Kenzaburō Ōe (Japan, 1994), Gao Xingjian (China, 2000), Orhan Pamuk (Turkey, 2006), Mo Yan (China, 2012), and Han Kang (South Korea, 2024).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Some may consider the American writer, Pearl S.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Mother Teresa of India and Shirin Ebadi of Iran were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for their significant and pioneering efforts for democracy and human rights, especially for the rights of women and children.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Ebadi is the first Iranian and the first Muslim woman to receive the prize.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Another Nobel Peace Prize winner is Aung San Suu Kyi from Burma for her peaceful and non-violent struggle under a military dictatorship in Burma.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] She is a nonviolent pro-democracy activist and leader of the National League for Democracy in Burma (Myanmar) and a noted prisoner of conscience.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] She is a Buddhist and was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Chinese dissident Liu Xiaobo was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for "his long and non-violent struggle for fundamental human rights in China" on 8 October 2010.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] He is the first Chinese citizen to be awarded a Nobel Prize of any kind while residing in China.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In 2014, Kailash Satyarthi from India and Malala Yousafzai from Pakistan were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize "for their struggle against the suppression of children and young people and for the right of all children to education".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Raman is the first Asian to get a Nobel prize in Sciences.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] He won the Nobel Prize in Physics "for his work on the scattering of light and for the discovery of the effect named after him".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Japan has won the most Nobel Prizes of any Asian nation with 24 followed by India which has won 13.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] 1933) is an Indian economist who was awarded the 1998 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences for his contributions to welfare economics and social choice theory, and for his interest in the problems of society's poorest members.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Most of the said awardees are from Japan and Israel except for Chandrasekhar and Raman (India), Abdus Salam (Pakistan), Arafat (Palestinian Territories), Kim (South Korea), and Horta and Belo (Timor-Leste).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] In 2006, the Bangladeshi Muhammad Yunus of was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for the establishment of Grameen Bank, a community development bank that lends money to poor people, especially women.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] He is known for the concept of micro credit which, allows poor and destitute people to borrow money.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The borrowers pay back money within the specified period and defaulting is very low.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] Yunus also became the leader of an interim government after the 2024 Bangladesh quota reform movement.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/asia-p02] The Dalai Lama received the Nobel Peace Prize, in Oslo, Norway in 1989.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Some reasons for aviculture are: breeding birds as a hobby, a business like a zoo, or sometimes for research and conservation purposes to preserve and protect some endangered avian species that are at risk due to habitat destruction, the illegal wildlife trade, diseases, and natural disasters.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Aviculture encourages conservation, provides education about avian species, provides companion birds for the public, and includes research on avian behaviour.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Popular birds people like to keep and breed include budgerigars, cockatiels, finches, macaws, domestic canaries, columbidae (pigeons and doves), loriini (lories and lorikeets), cockatoos, conures, and African grey parrots.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Aviculture has been practiced for thousands of years in human history, with evidence of bird keeping found in ancient civilizations where birds were kept for food, beauty, communication, and symbolism.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In the modern context, aviculture has evolved into a multidisciplinary field that intersects with biology, ecology, veterinary science, and conservation management.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Those who practice aviculture are "aviculturists." Aviculturists may work in private collections, breeding facilities, zoos, sanctuaries, or research institutions, each practicing for different goals such as genetic management, education, or species recovery.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Nowadays, aviculture is also a popular hobby, with birdkeeping enthusiasts from all over the world.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] A major part of also its role in bird conservation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Captive breeding programs have helped protect endangered species by maintaining healthy populations in controlled environments.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Sometimes these programs also support the reintroduction of birds into the wild.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Responsible aviculture places strong importance on the welfare of the birds, including proper housing, balanced nutrition, good health care, and opportunities for natural behaviors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] As many global issues such as habitat loss, climate change, and illegal wildlife trade continue to threaten bird populations, aviculture remains both useful and controversial.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] It is viewed as a tool that can support education, research, and conservation when practiced ethically and responsibly.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In the UK, the Avicultural Society was formed in 1894 and the Foreign Bird League in 1932.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In 1973, Aviornis was created, a bird-breeding association present in several European countries.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The oldest avicultural society in the United States is the Avicultural Society of America, founded in 1927.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The ASA produces a bi-monthly magazine, *ASA Avicultural Bulletin*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The ASA is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization that focuses on breeding, conservation, restoration and education.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The first avicultural society in Australia was The Avicultural Society of South Australia, founded in 1928.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] It is now promoted with the name Bird Keeping in Australia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The two major national avicultural societies in the United States are the American Federation of Aviculture and the Avicultural Society of America, founded in 1927.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The Budgerigar Society was formed in 1925.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The Avicultural Society of South Australia (founded in 1928) produces a monthly full-colour magazine, *Bird Keeping in Australia*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The practice of bird keeping can be traced back in time for over 6,000 years ago, There has been a record to indicate that birds have been kept in captivity for poultry, According to H.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Scullard (as cited in Johnson, Lee R.,1968), Excavations among the Terramare people have revealed that these early inhabitants of peninsula had domesticated the chicken and the duck as early as 1700 B.C.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] According to Best and Walker, 2020, There are even older records of pigeons being kept in Mesopotamia as early as 4500 B.C.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Aviculture has been a part of human civilisation for many purposes, civilisations have translocated bird species, both domesticated and non-domesticated, across regions to serve as food, decorative elements, hunting stock, or companions.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] 2015). so much that "birds have colonised and occupied all major landforms, oceans, and islands of the world" (p.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] 1) A few species have undergone full domestication, whereas others have been raised in captive environments over through generations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Domestication of poultry was significantly tied to the development of early agriculture (J Archaeol Res, 2025).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In Southeast Asia, the transition from wild birds to domestic chickens occurred between 1650 and 1250 B.C., where dry rice and millet are cultivated across the region, drawing wild red junglefowl into human settlements (Peters et al., 2022).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] This created a relationship between the species and human, making them grow into a member of human societies.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The early avian relationships were not uniform; while some species became fully domestic, others were kept in managed or captive states to fulfil specific cultural and practical roles.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The goose (Anser cygnoides) is likely the first bird species to be kept.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Recent genetic and archaeological evidence has indicated that there are breeding taking place outside the current area where geese naturally breed today (Shi et al., 2006).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Another breed that has a long history of relationship with human is pigeon, which descended from rock doves (Columba livia).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] With many records of self-domesticated near human colonies, then exploited for consumption.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The oldest records dated back to the birds being sustainably harvested by Neanderthals (Blasco et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Meanwhile Ancient Egyptians kept them for ceremonial offerings, and Greek have statues and vases dated to the 5th century BC depict people holding the birds (Hawes 1984).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In Europe, the medieval period witnessed widespread use of dovecotes, which were a symbol of status as humans began to encourage birds to roost.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The global movement of birds can be divided into two main periods.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The first period is moved by European Acclimatisation Societies occurring between the 18th and 20th centuries, as the human world was at the age of discovery and colonisation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The movements people also created transportation and trading of many species and introducing species of birds to new colonies as a result.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The second period; the era of the international trade in wild birds for bird-keeping from the late-twentieth century to the nowadays.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In this era of international trade typically moves birds in reverse direction from the previous era, often moving from former colonies in South America, Africa, and Southeast Asia toward Europe and North America.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Birds exhibit strong sensitivity to changes in environmental conditions, and their responses vary significantly between species due to differences in ecological traits.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Ground-nesting and habitat specialists (e.g., larks, bustards) are especially vulnerable.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] For instance, The Great Bustard ( Otis tarda ), which demands large, intact grassland habitats free from disturbance for lekking and nesting, shows a decrease in population with even moderate increases in human infrastructure and grazing pressure (Rocha et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In comparison to some generalist species such as the corvids may initially tolerate or even gain advantage from low-intensity disturbance as a consequence of expanded foraging opportunities in disturbed patches (Han et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] 2025), although continued persistence often obscure broader community degradation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] At the community level, steppe bird assemblages have been significantly altered by the increasing of human footprint.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Declines in species richness and abundance have consistently been reported by researchers along gradients of disturbance intensity, particularly outwit moderate levels of grazing to habitat conversion (Liang et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Additionally, activities relate to human can expose wildlife to pesticides and other pollutants, placing additional stress on bird populations (Tassin de Montaigu and Goulson 2020; Rigal et al.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Birds that have been kept in captivity and subsequently released into the wild survival chances depend on various factors.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Captive breeds, and hand-reared birds that have imprinted on humans typically do not survive.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Upon release, they frequently retreat to the cage for security.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Several captive birds have permission to free fly, subsequently return for food and protection.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Hand-reared birds commonly show reduced breeding success compared to parent-reared birds, so aviculturists handle breeding stock noticeably less than birds intended to be companion animals.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Avians that are specially bred to be released into the wild receive different treatment and potentially have little or no human contact, while encouraging to forage by more natural methods.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Private aviculturists have increasing responsibility in the breeding of rare or endangered species to accumulate stocks for return to the wild.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Considerate the fact that numerous uncommon or rare birds are plentiful in aviaries, breeding programs have enlisted the support of private aviculturists by several government conservation departments.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Changes in antipredator behaviour in captivity have been suggest explaining the higher invasiveness of wild-caught exotic species.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] An intraspecific comparison between wild-caught and captive-breed's first generation shows an expeditious behavioural decrease in captivity (individual lifetime) rather than to differences among species (evolutionary exposure).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Addition to the current of avian invasions, the proportion of individuals exhibiting antipredator responses within a species was positively associated with the likelihood of that species escaping and breeding in the wild.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In contrast to earlier intentional introductions, recent and ongoing avian invasions emerge from the accidental escape of globally traded cage birds.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In this hypothetical scenario, Carrete & Tella reported that wild-caught cage bird species are considerably more incline to escaping and becoming invaders rather than captive-bred, regardless of their accessibility on the pet market.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] As a matter of fact, responses to acute stress differ from wild-caught and captive-bred individuals.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Corticosterone (CORT) responses to acute stress last longer in wild-caught individuals, compare to captive-bred birds, both at inter- and intra-specific levels.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The prolong response present in wild-caught birds could assist them escape from cages and have greater survival chances when encountering challenges in new environments, perhaps adding to their higher invasiveness.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Numerous birds have been selectively bred for domestication over generations, which produce behavioural changes as a consequence.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Therefore, the antipredator behaviour changing of captive-bred birds can be consequence of their detachment from predators as well as founder effects and/or artificial (human) selection.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] In addition, individual behavioural traits frequently show correlation, including those individuals that display relatively bold behaviour toward predators are prone to be more towards conspecifics, and thus, developing a medium-term loss of antipredatory response at the population level.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Exotic bird populations are complicate to control once they are established and reinforce the polemic, controversial demand for prohibit the trade of wild-caught birds as a preventive action (see review in).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] A permanent trade ban (as enforced in Spain by law Real Decreto 630 in 2013) worldwide would be effortless and effective route of controlling current, and preventing future, exotic invasions, while captive breeding can satisfy the social demand for exotic cage birds without risks.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Avian species are commonly kept in captivity for humans' enjoyment and pleasure.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Companion birds are typically considered as an interactive animal that recognizes the owner, developing a human to animal bonds.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] The purpose of keeping a companion is to propagate the species, provide companionship, and enjoyment for the owner.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Despite common assumptions, the breeding of exotic birds in captivity has a potentially negative impact on the species in the wild.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Throughout the history the increasing popularity of keeping exotic animals as pet, Wild caught or captive bred, frequently leads to a subsequent increase in the illegal trafficking of their wild counterparts.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Official captive propagation and reintroduction programs are generally pursued only as a final measure, demanding substantial cost and over many decades of effort.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] To achieve a favorable outcome, most committed captive breeding of endangered wildlife species must be performed deprived of any human contact.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] From juvenile bird's predator avoidance, foraging, and social interaction are required skills to ensure a good chance of survival in the wild.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Avian Conservation programs signify the commitment to safeguarding bird species and their natural environments.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Central to ecological stability, it acknowledges the crucial need to maintain biodiversity within ecosystems.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] This program includes approaches to reduce threats such as habitat degradation, the impacts of climate change, environmental contamination, and guarantees long-term survival of diverse avian populations.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Reliable aviculture for conservation objective advocates the breeding of specific species in captivity with the mission and expectation of introducing them back into the wild.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Falconry is the traditional practice of managing and hunting with trained birds of prey.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] This is one of the oldest applications of aviculture that have been documented, with the evidence of prehistoric cave paintings depicted falconry work, dated to the 13th century BCE.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] Depending on the country, wild birds of prey may be legally trapped by falconers, or obtain birds bred in captivity.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/aviculture] After completing in training, multiple falconers will release their peak physical condition birds into the wild with the lifetime ability to hunt prey.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The historical centre of the city is situated in the Ravensberg Basin north of the Teutoburg Forest hill range, but modern Bielefeld extends across the range and further south into the flat Westphalian Basin.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The city is situated on the *Hermannsweg*, a hiking trail that runs for 156 km along the ridges of the Teutoburg Forest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld is home to a significant number of internationally operating companies, including Dr.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Oetker, DMG Mori (former Gildemeister), Möller Group, Goldbeck and Schüco.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It has a university and several technical colleges (*Fachhochschulen*).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld is also known for the Bethel Foundation.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Founded in 1214 by Count Hermann IV of Ravensberg to guard a pass crossing the Teutoburg Forest, Bielefeld was the "city of linen" as a minor member of the Hanseatic League, known for bleachfields into the 19th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Peace of Westphalia in 1648 turned Ravensberg, from 1719 Minden-Ravensberg, into a part of Brandenburg–Prussia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] When Prussia lost its western territories to French control in 1807, Bielefeld became part of the Kingdom of Westphalia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] In 1813 the region reverted back to the Kingdom of Prussia, and following the defeat of France and the Congress of Vienna in 1815 Bielefeld was incorporated into the newly formed Province of Westphalia.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] After the Cologne-Minden railway opened in 1849, the Bozi brothers constructed the first large mechanised spinning mill in 1851.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Ravensberg Spinning Mill was built from 1854 to 1857, and metal works began to open in the 1860s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Founded in 1867 as a Bielefeld sewing machine repair company, Dürkoppwerke AG employed 1,665 people in 1892; it used Waffenamt code "WaA547" from 1938 to 1939 as the Dürkopp-Werke, and merged with other Bielefeld companies to form Dürkopp Adler AG in 1990.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Between 1904 and 1930, Bielefeld grew, opening a rebuilt railway station, a municipal theatre, and finally, the Rudolf-Oetker-Halle concert hall, renowned for its excellent acoustics.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Dürkopp car was produced from 1898 to 1927.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] After printing emergency money (German: *Notgeld*) in 1923 during the inflation in the Weimar Republic, Bielefeld was one of several towns that printed very attractive and highly collectable banknotes with designs on silk, linen and velvet.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] These pieces were issued by the Bielefeld Stadtsparkasse (town's savings bank) and were sent all around the world in the early 1920s.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] These pieces are known as *Stoffgeld* – that is, money made from fabric.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The town's synagogue was burned in 1938 during the *Kristallnacht* pogrom carried out against Jewish population.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] In 1944, Boeing B-17 Flying Fortresses of the USAAF bombed the gas works at Bielefeld on 20 September and the marshaling yard on 30 September; Bielefeld was bombed again on 7 October and the RAF bombed the town on the night of 4/5 December.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] On 17 January 1945, B-17s bombed the nearby Paderborn marshalling yard, and the railway viaduct in the suburb of Schildesche.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] On 14 March the RAF bombed the viaduct again, wrecking it.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] This was the first use of the RAF's 10 tonne Grand Slam bomb.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] American troops entered the city in April 1945.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Until the 1980s there was a large British presence in the barracks housing the headquarters of the British First Corps and support units, as well as schools, NAAFI shops, officers' and sergeants' messes and several estates of married quarters.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The British presence was heavily scaled back after the reunification of Germany and most of the infrastructure has disappeared, with the final departure in 2020.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] As a part of larger municipal reforms in North Rhine-Westphalia, the city of Bielefeld was merged with the surrounding district of Bielefeld to form the “district-free city” of Bielefeld on 1 January 1973.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] This created the administrative structures and borders that the city has to this day.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] For the first time, Bielefeld was extended to the south side of the Teutoburg Forest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The city’s population rose from 167,000 to 320,000 and its area increased more than five-fold, from 48 to 259 km².
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Starting in 1994, the city has been the subject of the humorous Bielefeld conspiracy, which satirises conspiracy theories by claiming that the city does not exist.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*; Trewartha: *Dobk*).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The average annual high temperature is 14.6 °C (58.3 °F), the annual low temperature is 5.4 °C (41.7 °F), and the annual precipitation is 866.4 millimetres (34.11 inches).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld was a linen-producing town, and in the early 1920s the Town's Savings Bank (Stadtsparkasse) issued money made of linen, silk and velvet.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] In addition to the manufacture of home appliances and various heavy industries, Bielefeld companies include Dr.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Oetker (food manufacturing), Möller Group (leather products and plastics), Seidensticker (clothing and textiles) and Bethel Institution with 17.000 employees.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld University was founded in 1969.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The first professors included the well-known German sociologist Niklas Luhmann.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld has several vocational schools like Berufskolleg Senne. and Berufskolleg Bethel.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] These schools focus on hands-on training in various fields, including business, healthcare, and technical disciplines.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The current mayor (*Oberbürgermeister*) of Bielefeld is Christiana Bauer of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), who was elected in 2025.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Bielefeld city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The most recent city council election was held on 13 September 2020.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The SPD, the Greens, and the Left made a coalition with 35 of the 66 seats in the council.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Two major *autobahns*, the A 2 and A 33, intersect in the south east of Bielefeld.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The *Ostwestfalendamm* expressway connects the two parts of the city, naturally divided by the Teutoburg Forest.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld Hauptbahnhof, the main railway station of Bielefeld, is on the Hamm–Minden railway and is part of the German ICE high-speed railroad system.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The main station for intercity bus services is Brackwede station.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld has a small airstrip, Flugplatz Bielefeld, in the Senne district but is mainly served by the three larger airports nearby, Paderborn Lippstadt Airport, Münster Osnabrück Airport and Hannover Airport.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Bielefeld boasts a well-developed public transport system, served mainly by the companies *moBiel* (formerly *Stadtwerke Bielefeld – Verkehrsbetriebe*) and "BVO".
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Bielefeld Stadtbahn has four major lines and regional trains connect different parts of the city with nearby counties.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Sparrenburg Castle is Bielefeld's characteristic landmark.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It was built between 1240 and 1250 by Count Ludwig von Ravensberg.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The 37-metre-high (121 ft) tower and the catacombs of the castle are open to the public.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Linen Weavers' Monument, with the German name *Leineweber-Denkmal*, created by the Tyrolean sculptor Perathoner, has been one of Bielefeld's most recognisable symbols for over 100 years.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It stands as a reminder of the time when the city gained importance through the production of linen, with the traditional crafts of spinning and weaving, and its high-quality linen became known worldwide, characterised by its own seal of quality.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The Old City Hall (*Altes Rathaus*) was built in 1904 and still serves the same function.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Its façade reflects the so-called Weserrenaissance and features elements of various architectural styles, including Gothic and Renaissance.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Though the mayor still holds office in the Old City Hall, most of the city's administration is housed in the adjacent New City Hall (*Neues Rathaus*).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The City Theatre (*Stadttheater*) is part of the same architectural ensemble as the Old City Hall, also built in 1904.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It has a notable Jugendstil façade, is Bielefeld's largest theatre and home of the Bielefeld Opera.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Another theatre (*Theater am Alten Markt*) resides in the former town hall building on the Old Market Square (*Alter Markt*), which also contains a row of restored 16th and 17th-century townhouses with noteworthy late Gothic and Weser Renaissance style façades (*Bürgerhäuser am Alten Markt*).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The oldest city church is *Altstädter Nicolaikirche*.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It is a Gothic hall church with a height of 81.5 m (267 ft).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It was founded in 1236 by the Bishop of Paderborn, and enlarged at the beginning of the 14th century.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The church was damaged in World War II and later rebuilt.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Three times a day, a carillon can be heard.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The most valuable treasure of this church is a carved altar from Antwerp, decorated with 250 figures.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] A small museum housed within illustrates the history of the church up to World War II.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The largest church is the *Neustädter Marienkirche*, a Gothic hall church dating back to 1293, completed 1512.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It stands 78 m (256 ft) tall and has a length of 52 m (171 ft).
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] Historically speaking, this building is considered to be the most precious possession of the town.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] It was the starting point of the Protestant Reformation in Bielefeld in 1553.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] A valuable wing-altar with 13 pictures, known as the *Marienaltar* is also kept inside.
[src:funds-for-endangered-parrots/bielefeld] The baroque spires were destroyed in World War II and later replaced by two unusually-shaped "Gothic" clocktowers.
